	abstract = {The afterword broadly discusses the need for EU digital regulation to be ‘future-proofed’. Considering the various areas discussed in each chapter of the volume—data protection in relation to other recent legislative initiatives, algorithmic transparency of the so-called ‘black box’, legal protection by design in automated decision-making, the functioning of EU interoperability and the rules of data sharing, the avenues for accountability in the EU architecture of data-led security—the risk of an instrumental use of technology that is excessive in legal terms is highlighted. The chapter points out how this might be accentuated through the shifting boundaries of EU law. EU digital regulatory initiatives challenge the preservation of EU values and fundamental rights. At the same time, new regulation is part of digital transformation, the legitimacy of which is under fire. © Deirdre Curtin, Mariavittoria Catanzariti and the contributors 2023.},
