	affiliations = {School of Government of Universidad de los Andes, Colombia; Nariño, Colombia},
	abstract = {The adoption of artificial intelligence (AI) and other algorithmic technologies in the public sector is steadily increasing worldwide, with transparency being one of the most common principles in AI guidelines. However, only a few national and subnational governments proactively inform citizens about using these systems. This chapter examines how public repositories of algorithms can contribute to proactive algorithmic transparency. It analyzes the case of the Colombian national government's repositories and the levels of transparency regarding the acquisition, development, piloting, adoption, and use of automated decision-making (ADM) systems. A novel database of ADM systems in the Colombian public sector is also presented. It concludes that while the government publishes significant amounts of data about its ADM systems, the publicly available information is insufficient to make the algorithmic processes truly accountable in Colombia. The research follows a case study approach, with quantitative and qualitative data collected from public databases, institutional web pages, social networks, and press reports. Secondary sources included information from tech companies, news reports, gray literature published by multilateral entities and civil society organizations, and academic literature. Overall, the study highlights the need for governments to take proactive measures to ensure algorithmic transparency and accountability in the public sector. © The Editor and Contributing Authors Severally 2025. All rights reserved.},
