	affiliations = {School of Electrical Engineering and Informatics, Institut Teknologi Bandung, Indonesia; School of Applied Science, Telkom University, Bandung, Indonesia; Universitas Andi Djemma Palopo Palopo, Faculty of Engineering, Indonesia; Smart City and Community Innovation Center, Institut Teknologi Bandung, Bandung, Indonesia},
	abstract = {The Sensing as a Service (SenaaS) model, a cornerstone of the Internet of Things (IoT), is rapidly evolving with the integration of Artificial Intelligence (AI), transforming it from a data-provisioning utility into an automated decision-making ecosystem. This paper presents a philosophical inquiry into this paradigm, using the recently proposed Unified and Sustainable Sensing as a Service (USSenaaS) framework as a central case study. We deconstruct the SenaaS architecture as a distributed cognitive system and analyze its objectives through the lens of epistemological theories such as process reliabilism. This analysis is then extended to address the profound challenges and transformations brought by AI. We explore the shift from simple analytics to opaque black box AI models, the critical need for Explainable AI (XAI) to ensure trust and accountability, and the tension between the confirmationist nature of machine learning and the classical scientific principle of falsifiability. The paper argues that the convergence of SenaaS and AI necessitates a new philosophical grounding a critical holistic pragmatism that moves beyond the technical performance metrics exemplified by the USSenaaS framework to encompass the epistemological, ethical, and societal implications of automated, data-driven intelligence. © 2025 IEEE.},
