	year = {2025},
	journal = {Data Protection, Privacy and Artificial Intelligence: To Govern or To Be Governed,That is the Question},
	pages = {168 - 200},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105014582596?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Department of Criminology, Criminal Law and Social Law, Ghent University, Belgium; Department of Criminology, Criminal Law and Social Law at Ghent University and visiting professor of security sciences at the, University of Antwerp, Belgium},
	abstract = {The adoption of new data-driven methods is increasingly transforming both public and private sectors. Within the context of law enforcement, the increasing prevalence of big data and big data analytics is significantly reshaping decisionmaking processes at both operational and strategic levels. The emergence of ‘big data policing’ as a multifaced concept is progressively becoming a substantive approach to various aspects of policing and social control. Within the European Union (EU), applications of big data policing are regulated by existing primary and secondary EU laws. These include the Charter of Fundamental Rights, the Law Enforcement Directive (LED), the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), and the EU Artificial Intelligence Act (AI Act). Linked to the right to human intervention (Article 22 GDPR, Article 11 LED) and right to explanation in automated decision-making (Articles 13–15, 22 GDPR), governance mechanisms introduced in the AI Act consist of human agency and oversight, for high-risk AI systems (Article 14 AI Act), such as big data policing. However, the exact capabilities and characteristics of this oversight in relation to human agency throughout an application’s life cycle have not been specified. We set out to offer a targeted overview of how to operationalise human agency and oversight in the context of place-based big data policing throughout an application’s life-cycle. Key considerations and power-asymmetries arising in the core decision-making layers (ie, project set-up, data preparation, model selection and deployment), need to be clearly identified and aligned with a decision-maker’s agency, ultimately narrowing the error margin and facilitating clear oversight protocols. We highlight the need for evaluation throughout the life-cycle of the project and mainstreaming ethical guidelines, connecting these within the context of data justice, as well as utilising explainability and explainable AI in big data policing applications. Moreover, evaluation should occur throughout the layers to anticipate future challenges, while learning from past ones. Essentially, oversight needs to be addressed by every decisionmaker, ie humans in and on the loop, within the scope of their respective agency, to govern big data policing applications effectively. © The editors and contributors severally 2025. All rights reserved 2017.},
	author_keywords = {AI Act; Big Data; Decision-Making; Explainability and Explainable AI; GDPR; Human Intervention; Human Oversight and Agency; Place-based Policing; Power Asymmetries; Right to Explanation; Trustworthiness},
	keywords = {Advanced Analytics; Artificial life; Behavioral research; Decision making; Ethical aspects; International law; Law enforcement; Life cycle; Security of data; Artificial intelligence act; Decisions makings; Explainability and explainable AI; General data protection regulations; Human agency; Human intervention; Human oversight; Place-based; Place-based policing; Power; Power asymmetry; Right to explanation; Trustworthiness; Big data},
	publisher = {Bloomsbury Publishing Plc.},
