	affiliations = {Bina Nusantara University, Management Department, Binus Business School, Jakarta, 15143, Indonesia},
	abstract = {Outsourcing has become a dominant employment model in Jakarta; however, outsourcing recruitment often suffers from inefficiency, implicit bias, and a lack of transparency, raising concerns about fairness and compliance with labor regulations. Conventional machine learning (ML) approaches have been usually applied to candidate classification, yet their black-box nature limits interpretability and accountability. This study aims to address these shortcomings by proposing a neuro-symbolic artificial intelligence (NSAI) framework that integrates the predictive capacity of neural networks with the interpretability of symbolic reasoning. Drawing on theories of explainable AI and fairness in algorithmic decision-making, the research employs a quantitative and computational design. Primary recruitment datasets from Jakarta outsourcing firms were analyzed, and fairness-related HR policies were encoded into symbolic rules. The model's performance was evaluated using predictive metrics (precision, recall, F1-score, and AUC) as well as fairness measures (demographic parity, equalized odds, and disparate impact ratio). The results show that NSAI outperforms conventional ML models by maintaining high predictive accuracy while significantly improving fairness. The originality of this research lies in applying NSAI to Indonesia's outsourcing sector, demonstrating the dual capacity of NSAI to enhance both efficiency and ethical compliance. This provides a replicable framework for responsible AI the in HRTech sector. © 2025 IEEE.},
